RT @SpeakerRyan: Just now ‚Üí With a unanimous vote, the House passed legislation to reform the Congressional Accountability Act and help mak‚Ä¶
retweet_text: Just now ‚Üí With a unanimous vote, the House passed legislation to reform the Congressional Accountability Act and help make hostile workplaces in Congress a relic of the past. From Members to staff, no one should feel unsafe serving in Congress.

text: (5) The resolution prohibits Members of Congress from engaging in a sexual relationship with any staff member under their supervision and makes clear that sexual harassment is a violation of the Code of Official Conduct and will not be tolerated.
(4) The resolution paves the way for every Congressional office to have a clearly defined anti-harassment and anti-discrimination policy. This reform alone will result in greater awareness.
(3) The bill will ensure that Members of Congress, not taxpayers, are responsible for paying out sexual harassment settlements.

(2) The bill increases transparency by requiring that basic information about any sexual harassment or other claims be made public so the American people are fully aware of what is happening in the Congress.

(1) The bill makes the process of handling employment law claims smoother, faster, and fairer. The bill also creates an office of employee advocacy to ensure staff has access to legal counsel, just as Member offices are provided.
Our bipartisan bill includes a range of reforms to the way sexual harassment and other employment law claims are handled on Capitol Hill. Here are five that I am especially proud of:
This is a commonsense policy in almost all workplaces, and now Congress will play by the same rules. https://t.co/yb0WTyMxKJ
quoted_text: Change is coming to the U.S. House today: Lawmakers voting to add House Rule to explicitly prohibit lawmakers from having sexual relationships with staffers. Makes it an Ethics violation to do so. Part of broader effort to change culture of Capitol Hill following #metoo movement

mentions_screen_name: Nanacruze RepSpeier GreggHarper RepBrady SusanWBrooks RepTedDeutch HouseAdmnGOP HouseAdm_Dems

text: @loureynolds1940 Originally, Congress wasn't covered at all. This bill would do away with the slush fund and make Members personally financially responsible for harassment claims, not taxpayers. Taxpayer money should not and will not be used to settle claims against members going forward.

Our reform bill has been a truly bipartisan effort and an example of how Congress should work. Thanks to @RepSpeier, @GreggHarper, @RepBrady, @SusanWBrooks, @RepTedDeutch, @HouseAdmnGOP, & @HouseAdm_Dems for working with me on this substantive and transformative legislation.
mentions_screen_name: RepSpeier GreggHarper RepBrady SusanWBrooks RepTedDeutch HouseAdmnGOP HouseAdm_Dems

text: Our bipartisan reform bill will bring the Congressional workplace into the 21st Century and ensure that Congress plays by the same rules as the private sector.

@MSmittyRocks The bill would hold Members of Congress personally responsible for paying any penalties associated with the sexual harassment claims.

From the start, my goal has been to pursue a process that holds Members of Congress to the same standard as the rest of the country when it comes to allegations of sexual harassment. There should be no special treatment.
Additionally, transparency will be increased to make sure the American people are aware when a sexual harassment claim is settled by a Congressional office.

At a time when many people are overwhelmed with the world today, I want to share a few things that give me great hope.
